  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provision of Education in Emergencies to 29,440 conflict affected IDP girls and boys in Ninewa Governorate</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed programme is part of an integrated EiE, CPiE and WASH response to the Mosul crisis, comprising of the Education in Emergencies (EiE) inputs. With the proposed programme, Save the Children (SC) will continue and extend access to quality non formal EiE for 13,840 girls and 15,600 boys in Hamam al Alil and Qayarrah sub districts. While specific attention will be paid to ensuring girls are afforded with the same opportunities as boys to attend learning activities, current programming suggests that boys will be slightly more than girls. SC will target vulnerable out of school children to be absorbed  into NFE and ultimately support them to re-enter the formal system as appropriate and possible. The primary modality will be through the establishment and equipment of further TLSs as well as ongoing support to existing TLSs to expand access and continuity of education. Adequate age-and-gender-appropriate WASH facilities will be established at each site by our WASH team. Newly registered children will receive a student kit, and all TLSs will be provided with sufficient start up or replenishment teaching and learning materials. SC will ensure age and grade appropriate NFE content is provided to facilitators to support them in re-introducing children back to education. Education facilitators will be trained both on children&#x2019;s wellbeing (PSS, PFA, CSG, CPiE) as well as on how and what to teach (classroom management, pedagogy, curriculum and planning, basic literacy and numeracy etc.). SC will arrange for an accredited MRE organization to communicate lifesaving awareness messages to children and facilitators, our WASH team will provide hygiene promotion sessions and our CP team will arrange PSS activities for children in a newly established 4th afternoon shift. SC will ensure targeted and comprehensive awareness and outreach activities to ensure all TLSs are operating at full capacity and that as many children as possible are accessing education. In line with this, camp campaigns and community meetings will be arranged and PTAs established and trained.</narrative>
  </description>
